<paragraph id="1D4DB3A4BC43FCC2142072679D6AF327" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
As mentioned above, 
<taxonomicName id="5D61D8272A84C2762DCC7AE21F01918C" baseAuthorityName="Latzel" baseAuthorityYear="1884" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Bacillidesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bacillidesmus filiformis" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filiformis">
<emphasis id="85D0D4E28743BF3ED993CE8860791FE7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Bacillidesmus filiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to show some habitual and gonopodal similarities with 
<taxonomicName id="552D5DED9ACA337D296EDDB89818D171" authorityName="Tabacaru" authorityYear="1980" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopolydesmidae" genus="Banatodesmus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Banatodesmus" order="Polydesmida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BB7FE1149E8EA5301CB81B793B54EF5A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Banatodesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both taxa share sensilla basiconica of antennomere 6 completely enclosed in the pit, paraprocts with only two long setae each, and hypoproct with only two long distal setae. In addition, the solenomeral branch and the solenophore are oriented mostly antero-posteriorly rather than meso-laterally to each other.
</paragraph>
